00:09:54.900 --> 00:09:59.120
Other programs that can be used
to import and edit the maps

00:09:59.120 --> 00:10:03.270
include ithoughts, which is
available for a modest price,

00:10:03.270 --> 00:10:06.430
and XMind, an
open-source program

00:10:06.430 --> 00:10:10.120
that is available for free.

00:10:10.120 --> 00:10:12.800
Last but not least, if you
want to explore the maps

00:10:12.800 --> 00:10:15.820
but not edit them, the
easiest way to do so

00:10:15.820 --> 00:10:18.420
is to use the "flash"
based versions,

00:10:18.420 --> 00:10:21.460
which are available on
the CopyrightX website.

00:10:21.460 --> 00:10:24.080
To use those, you do not
need any software at all;

00:10:24.080 --> 00:10:28.040
they will open in
most modern browsers.

00:10:28.040 --> 00:10:31.350
Together, the two maps contains
all of my lecture notes

00:10:31.350 --> 00:10:35.730
for all 12 of these lectures,
plus links to a wide variety

00:10:35.730 --> 00:10:37.200
of additional materials.

00:10:37.200 --> 00:10:41.210
The result is that they contain
-- or provide access to --

00:10:41.210 --> 00:10:43.750
a large amount of
information and commentary.

00:10:43.750 --> 00:10:46.040
However, it is
important that you

00:10:46.040 --> 00:10:47.880
understand their limitations.

00:10:47.880 --> 00:10:51.680
In particular, you should
not think of the first map

00:10:51.680 --> 00:10:54.130
as the equivalent of a
treatise on copyright law;

00:10:54.130 --> 00:10:56.740
it is certainly not a
comprehensive survey

00:10:56.740 --> 00:11:00.480
of the law, and it contains some
opinionated material that would

00:11:00.480 --> 00:11:02.770
be inappropriate in a treatise.

00:11:02.770 --> 00:11:08.180
Rather it is a pedagogic aid --
a device intended to facilitate

00:11:08.180 --> 00:11:11.720
your understanding of --
and capacity to remember --

00:11:11.720 --> 00:11:15.960
the main features of
the copyright system.

00:11:15.960 --> 00:11:18.900
I modify both of the
maps with some frequency.

00:11:18.900 --> 00:11:21.560
Most often, I do this to
take into account changes

00:11:21.560 --> 00:11:23.710
in copyright
statutes or treaties

00:11:23.710 --> 00:11:25.920
or new judicial decisions.

00:11:25.920 --> 00:11:28.150
But I also sometimes
revise the maps

00:11:28.150 --> 00:11:30.330
when I change my mind
on a particular issue

00:11:30.330 --> 00:11:34.210
or when another commentator
deploys a novel argument.

00:11:34.210 --> 00:11:38.240
Accordingly, if you find the
maps useful in the future,

00:11:38.240 --> 00:11:40.910
you should probably check
the CopyrightX website

00:11:40.910 --> 00:11:44.010
to make sure that you have
the most current versions.

00:11:44.010 --> 00:11:47.250
I will try to keep the
maps reasonably up to date

00:11:47.250 --> 00:11:50.140
as long as I am able.

00:11:50.140 --> 00:11:52.290
Finally, if you have
suggestions concerning

00:11:52.290 --> 00:11:56.190
the content of either map
(bearing in mind, of course,

00:11:56.190 --> 00:11:58.810
their limited purposes),
feel free to e-mail

00:11:58.810 --> 00:12:02.880
me using the address listed
on the CopyrightX website.

00:12:02.880 --> 00:12:05.220
The same principle
applies to these lectures.

00:12:05.220 --> 00:12:07.810
If you have suggestions
concerning how they might be

00:12:07.810 --> 00:12:11.680
improved -- please let me
know, by sending a message

00:12:11.680 --> 00:12:13.005
to the same email address.

00:12:15.670 --> 00:12:18.320
This concludes the
introduction to lecture #1.

00:12:18.320 --> 00:12:20.560
In the next segment,
I will take up

00:12:20.560 --> 00:12:23.340
the first of the substantive
topics in the course:

00:12:23.340 --> 00:12:25.840
the concept of originality.

